  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Overview&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Cost metrics help a team monitor whether they are burning budget at a sustainable rate. Understanding whether they are&#xD;
    over or under budget enables the team to make informed project control decisions, such as adjusting scope, resources,&#xD;
    or time.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Cost status requires knowing two basic things:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Will the remainder of the project cost what we planned?&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        When the project is finished, will it have cost what we planned?&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Cost metrics&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The following metrics can help a team determine their cost status:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Core metrics&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.mgmt.common.extend_metrics-ibm/guidances/supportingmaterials/cost_per_unit_of_work_A9F11934.html&quot; guid=&quot;_eD4yALQyEd6HgZ8EwRW1Og&quot;>Cost Per Unit of Work&lt;/a> provides an estimated cost for delivering a single point.&#xD;
        The calculation is based on the cost of the team in a given iteration divided by the number of points delivered. As&#xD;
        team velocity increases over time, cost per unit of work decreases. However, if team velocity drops due to&#xD;
        unexpected rework or re-estimation, cost per unit of work increases. This can exceed the budget, potentially.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.mgmt.common.extend_metrics-ibm/guidances/supportingmaterials/planned_vs_actual_effort_DBE6C2F8.html&quot; guid=&quot;_ZkJQQLQyEd6HgZ8EwRW1Og&quot;>Planned Versus Actual Effort&lt;/a> can also help identify effects on cost.&#xD;
        &lt;em>Effort&lt;/em> translates the size of functionality (measured in points) into a detailed estimate, typically&#xD;
        measured in units of days or hours. A large difference between planned and actual effort expended can indicate&#xD;
        either that plans underestimated the amount of work or that the work is more difficult than anticipated. Increased&#xD;
        effort results in increased project costs.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Supplementary metrics&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Monitoring &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot; href=&quot;./../../core.mgmt.common.extend_metrics-ibm/guidances/supportingmaterials/maint_labor_cost_percentage_3CF402B7.html&quot; guid=&quot;_YDjEUCACEd6kWJaqU_SFSA&quot;>Development Versus Maintenance Costs&lt;/a> can help a team understand how their&#xD;
        development practices affect the cost of maintenance for the system.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Reporting project cost status in a dashboard&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The following dashboard example represents one way to calculate and report cost status. Teams can substitute metrics&#xD;
    that are already in place and used successfully in their organization for a customized cost report.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
    Produce this dashboard by harvesting metrics data and populating a spreadsheet, and using the graph features to&#xD;
    generate the dashboard report. Or, the team can use the spreadsheet as a data source and create a custom report in IBM&amp;reg;&#xD;
    Rational&amp;reg; Insight&amp;reg;. Our intent is to provide these types of dashboards over time as out of the box reports in IBM&amp;reg;&#xD;
    Rational&amp;reg; Insight&amp;reg;.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    To assess a project's Cost status with this dashboard, the following inputs are needed (provided by the core set of&#xD;
    Cost metrics and team-specific variables):&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;table title=&quot;&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; width=&quot;85%&quot; border=&quot;1&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;tbody>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;strong>&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>Value&lt;/font>&lt;/strong>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;strong>&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>Description&lt;/font>&lt;/strong>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                BUDGETED_ACTUAL_COST&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                Total amount budgeted for the project&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                TOTAL_POINTS&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                Total number of points that the team committed to deliver&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                VELOCITY&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                Number of points delivered in the last iteration.&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                COST_PER_POINT&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    For a given iteration, the cost of the team divided by the team's velocity&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                ESTIMATE_AT_COMPLETION&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    Currently expected total for the project based on the number of points that the team committed to&#xD;
                    deliver and cost per point. Calculated as follows: ESTIMATE_AT_COMPLETION = TOTAL_POINTS x&#xD;
                    COST_PER_POINT&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
    &lt;/tbody>&#xD;
&lt;/table>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Cost dashboard status is calculated as follows:&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;table style=&quot;WIDTH: 944px; HEIGHT: 382px&quot; width=&quot;944&quot; border=&quot;4&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;tbody>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;th scope=&quot;col&quot; width=&quot;99&quot; bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>Status&lt;/font>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/th>&#xD;
            &lt;th scope=&quot;col&quot; width=&quot;440&quot; bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>Definition&lt;/font>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/th>&#xD;
            &lt;th scope=&quot;col&quot; width=&quot;250&quot; bgcolor=&quot;#CCCCCC&quot;>&#xD;
                Actions to Take&#xD;
            &lt;/th>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#ff0000&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;strong>RED&lt;/strong>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#ffffff&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    ESTIMATE_AT_COMPLETION &amp;gt; BUDGETED_ACTUAL_COST&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    The current estimate for the project at completion is more than the amount budgeted.&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#ffffff&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    The following actions can be taken to improve Cost status:&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
                &lt;ul>&#xD;
                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                        Reduce scope for the release. Review the backlog with stakeholders and defer lower priority&#xD;
                        functionality to a later release.&#xD;
                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                        Determine if staff adjustments can be made without risking quality or schedule. Can some work items&#xD;
                        be handled with less expensive resources?&#xD;
                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                &lt;/ul>&lt;br />&#xD;
                &lt;br />&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#33CC66&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;strong>GREEN&lt;/strong>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    ESTIMATE_AT_COMPLETION &amp;lt;= BUDGETED_ACTUAL_COST&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    The current estimate for the project at completion is less than or equal to the amount budgeted&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                Good job! The project appears to be on budget. Confirm that stakeholder satisfaction is high and that they&#xD;
                are happy with the scope. Closely monitor the impact of scope increases, rework, and re-estimation.&#xD;
                Continue to monitor cost status at the end of each iteration for any change.&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td bgcolor=&quot;#ffff00&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;div align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;strong>YELLOW&lt;/strong>&#xD;
                &lt;/div>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                Status is red, but there is a plan in place to address the issue&lt;br />&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    Analyze cost metrics to determine the causes for the unexpected cost variance. Collaborate with&#xD;
                    stakeholders to determine what actions to take and then create a plan to address the issues. Follow the&#xD;
                    plan and monitor progress in each iteration until the status is green.&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    Consult the &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot; href=&quot;./../../publish.bus.practices_for_perf_measurement.base-ibm/customcategories/reduce_cost_EE4366D5.html&quot; guid=&quot;_5w8E4LbEEd6_i8GY7ieNyA&quot;>Cost Value Traceability Tree&lt;/a> which can help you identify strategies&#xD;
                    and solutions to reduce costs.&lt;br />&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
    &lt;/tbody>&#xD;
&lt;/table>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This cost dashboard calculation is based only on the cost of staff hours for the development team and it uses points as&#xD;
    the unit of measure for determining ESTIMATE_AT_COMPLETION. You can also use effort for this calculation.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Considerations&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;table title=&quot;&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;2&quot; width=&quot;85%&quot; border=&quot;1&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;tbody>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                Other costs&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                Although this dashboard monitors the cost of staff hours needed to develop the system, other costs&#xD;
                associated with software development (hardware and maintenance for example) should be monitored to reduce&#xD;
                the overall cost of the system.&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                Impact of defects&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;p>&#xD;
                    Typically, the later a defect is found, the more expensive it is to address. Reducing the time between&#xD;
                    developing code and validating it can significantly reduce costs.&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                Impact of process&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                Overhead related to non-essential meetings, documentation, and procedures can negatively impact the&#xD;
                productivity of the team, thereby increasing costs.&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                Automation&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                Tools that automate software development processes, such as automated testing tools, can reduce the cost of&#xD;
                delivering the system.&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td>&#xD;
                &lt;br />&#xD;
                &amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
    &lt;/tbody>&#xD;
&lt;/table>&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Pitfalls and countermeasures&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Velocity must stabilize in order for the cost per point to be useful. In early iterations, velocity is typically&#xD;
        lower so it is not a good indication of the team's potential productivity.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Delivering within budget as a criterion for success can be misleading. The team can meet the cost estimate to the&#xD;
        dollar, but if the product is missing half of its expected functionality, or if there are serious quality issues,&#xD;
        it will probably not be successful. It is important to analyze the suggested countermeasures for each supporting&#xD;
        cost metric to confirm that they are producing the appropriate behavior.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></mainDescription>
